Your problem can be eliminated with a little change to your code, instead of using links you can instead used forms and buttons. Then you can POST the data and its passed along in the background.

There is another option and as this is an Ecommerce platform it will have little impact because you will already want to use sessions, that is: store the data into the php session.

However, at this stage I feel that might be beyond your capability, not that I am discouraging or disparaging you in any way. So, my answer is to use form and POST it.

    &lt;form action=&quot;some_page&quot; method=&quot;post&quot;&gt;
        &lt;button type=&quot;submit&quot; name=&quot;unique_name&quot; value=&quot;&lt;?php echo $id_here; ?&gt;&quot; class=&quot;btn-link&quot;&gt;Go&lt;/button&gt;
    &lt;/form&gt;

    // inside the code access it as follows: $_POST[&#39;unique_name&#39;];

One work or caution, you really must make sure that what you receive from the form/url params or any user input is exactly what you expect. IE you need to be validating and possibly sanitising your users information. If you always remember that all user supplied data is extremely high risk then you wont go far wrong.


DO NOT DO THIS:

    SELECT something FROM somewhere WHERE something=&quot;$_GET[&#39;something&#39;]&quot;

That select statement is using $_GET directly, instead use prepared statements, if you are unsure of those, look into PDO or myqli prepared statements for more information on how you can reduce the risk of such user data.

